04133nam a22005055i 9780773576049DE-B159720240306124542.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240306t20092009xxc    fo  d z      eng d  a97807735760497 a10.1515/97807735760492doi  a(DE-B1597)656647  a(OCoLC)1394872769  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  axxccCA 4aF1034.3.F66bR88 2009eb 7aBIO0100002bisacsh04a327.7100921 aRuud, Charles A., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut14aThe Constant Diplomat :bRobert Ford in Moscow /cCharles A. Ruud. 1aMontreal ;aKingston ;aLondon ;aChicago : bMcGill-Queen's University Press, c[2009] 4c©2009  a1 online resource (344 p.) :b10 b&w photos  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFront Matter -- tContents -- tPreface -- tAcknowledgments -- tThe Ambassador in Training -- tThereza and Encounters with Russia -- tPolitics under Khrushchev -- tBrezhnev, the Flawed Leader -- tThe Soviets under Threat -- tTrudeau’s Opening -- tTrudeau in Moscow -- tTrudeau after the Peak -- tSoviet Meetings -- tThe Decline of the ussr -- tThe Soviet Embassy, Ottawa -- tFinal Things -- tA Retrospective Look -- tAppendices -- tA Soviet Province -- tEarly Travels with Ford, 1952–1953 -- tTravels with Ford, 1954–1972 -- tTravels with the Ambassador, 1978–1979 -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aRobert A.D. Ford had a distinguished diplomatic career that included an unprecedented sixteen years as Canadian ambassador to the Soviet Union during some of the most turbulent and important years of the Cold War (1964-80). Relying heavily on first-person testimony, including several interviews with Ford himself, Charles Ruud takes the reader behind the official announcements, revealing Ford's thoughts and actions as he dealt with what was then seen as the great arch-enemy of Western democratic nations. During his tenure as ambassador Ford was in frequent contact with Moscow's rulers and aware of their struggles, hopes, plans, and fears. Although they appeared powerful, Ford insisted that they sat uneasily on their Kremlin thrones. He showed their shortcomings and the flaws of their system at moments of apparent triumph and warned against miscalculating their strength. Shaped by centuries of Russian tsarism and by Communist ideology, Soviet leaders distrusted the world outside their borders and often failed to understand it, making mistakes and then compounding them, always without acknowledgment. The Constant Diplomat uncovers the experiences that informed Ford's capacity to understand the Russians and provides a clear picture of the evolving Soviet domestic, political, social, and cultural scene from the late Stalin era through to the end of the Brezhnev regime.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 7aBIOGRAPHY & AUTOBIOGRAPHY / Political.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Complete eBook-Package Pre-2010z978311127416408iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Upgrade eBook-Package pre 2010z978311127724040uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978077357604940uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780773576049423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780773576049/original  a978-3-11-127416-4  ACUP Complete eBook-Package Pre-2010b2010  a978-3-11-127724-0  ACUP Upgrade eBook-Package pre 2010b2010  aGBV-deGruyter-alles